  "text": "d φ is the unique Bregman divergence associated with the categorical distribution which, as detailed in example 10 from [CITATION_1] , is the discrete KL divergence and ψ z jt ,w jt is the entry of the topic vector associated with the topic indexed by z jt at the entry corresponding to the word at token w jt . This KL divergence will correspond to a single term of the form x log(x/y), where x = 1 since we are considering a single token of a word in a document. Thus, for a particular token, the KL divergence simply equals − log ψ z jt ,w jt . Note that when plugging in − log ψ z jt ,w jt into (5), we obtain exactly the original probability for word token w jt that we had in the original multinomial distribution. We will write the KL-divergence d φ (1, ψ z jt ,w jt ) as KL(w jt , ψ z jt ), wherew jt is an indicator vector for the word at token w jt .",
